{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <h1>Cookie &amp; LocalStorage Management</h1>
    <p>
        Rhapsody provides a secure, modern API for managing browser cookies and <code>localStorage</code> directly from your PHP controllers and Twig templates. Both systems are designed with security and ease of use in mind, leveraging PHP 8.4 features like enums and typed properties.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Cookie Management</h2>
    <p>
        The <code>Rhapsody\Core\Storage\Cookie</code> class offers a static API to set, get, and delete cookies with secure defaults. All cookie values are <strong>encrypted</strong> using AES-256-CBC and signed with your application's <code>APP_KEY</code>, preventing client-side tampering.
    </p>

    <h3>Configuration</h3>
    <p>
        Before using cookies, ensure your <code>.env</code> file contains a 32-character encryption key:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">APP_KEY=your-32-character-secret-key</code></pre>
    <p>
        Generate one with: <code>php -r "echo bin2hex(random_bytes(16));"</code>
    </p>

    <h3>PHP Usage</h3>
    <pre><code class="language-php">use Rhapsody\Core\Storage\Cookie;
use Rhapsody\Core\Storage\SameSite;

// Set a cookie (expires in 1 day)
Cookie::set('theme', 'dark', 86400);

// Set a cookie with custom SameSite
Cookie::set('preferences', ['notifications' => true], 3600, '/', null, true, true, SameSite::Strict);

// Get a cookie value
$theme = Cookie::get('theme', 'light');

// Check if a cookie exists
if (Cookie::has('user_id')) {
    // ...
}

// Delete a cookie
Cookie::delete('theme');

// Get all cookies (decrypted and decoded)
$all = Cookie::all();</code></pre>

    <p>
        The <code>Cookie::set()</code> method accepts the following parameters (all with secure defaults):
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>name</code> – the cookie name</li>
        <li><code>value</code> – can be a string, array, or any JSON-serializable value</li>
        <li><code>expiry</code> – lifetime in seconds (0 = session cookie)</li>
        <li><code>path</code> – cookie path (default: <code>/</code>)</li>
        <li><code>domain</code> – optional domain</li>
        <li><code>secure</code> – <code>true</code> (HTTPS only) by default</li>
        <li><code>httpOnly</code> – <code>true</code> (no JavaScript access) by default</li>
        <li><code>sameSite</code> – <code>SameSite::Lax</code>, <code>Strict</code>, or <code>None</code> (enum)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Twig Functions</h3>
    <p>
        The following Twig functions are available to work with cookies directly in your templates:
    </p>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full border-collapse bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
            <thead>
                <tr class="bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700">
                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Function</th>
                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Description</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>cookie_get(name, default)</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Returns the value of a cookie, or the default if not set.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>cookie_set(name, value, expiry, path, domain, secure, httpOnly, sameSite)</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Sets a cookie (returns nothing, outputs a <code>Set-Cookie</code> header).</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>cookie_has(name)</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Returns <code>true</code> if the cookie exists.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td class="p-3"><code>cookie_delete(name, path, domain)</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Deletes the cookie.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h4>Example in Twig</h4>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">&#123;# Check if the user has a preference #&#125;
&#123;% if cookie_has('theme') %&#125;
    &#123;% set theme = cookie_get('theme') %&#125;
&#123;% else %&#125;
    &#123;% set theme = 'light' %&#125;
&#123;% endif %&#125;

&#123;# Set a cookie after a form submission (e.g., from a controller) #&#125;
&#123;&#123; cookie_set('user_id', user.id, 86400) &#125;&#125;</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>LocalStorage Management</h2>
    <p>
        The <code>Rhapsody\Core\Storage\LocalStorage</code> class generates JavaScript snippets that manipulate the browser's <code>localStorage</code>. This is useful for client-side preferences, temporary data, or caching.
    </p>

    <h3>PHP Usage</h3>
    <p>
        All methods return a <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> tag ready to be output in your views.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">use Rhapsody\Core\Storage\LocalStorage;

// Generate a script that sets a localStorage item
echo LocalStorage::set('user_preferences', ['theme' => 'dark']);

// Generate a script that gets an item and calls a callback
echo LocalStorage::get('user_id', 'handleUserId');

// Remove an item
echo LocalStorage::remove('temp_data');

// Clear all localStorage
echo LocalStorage::clear();</code></pre>

    <h3>Twig Functions</h3>
    <p>
        The following Twig functions output <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> tags directly. Use them with the <code>&#123;&#123; ... &#125;&#125;</code> syntax (not <code>|raw</code>, as they are already safe).
    </p>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full border-collapse bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
            <thead>
                <tr class="bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700">
                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Function</th>
                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Description</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>localstorage_set(key, value, jsonEncode = true)</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Sets a <code>localStorage</code> item. If <code>jsonEncode</code> is <code>true</code>, the value is JSON-encoded.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>localstorage_remove(key)</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Removes a <code>localStorage</code> item.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td class="p-3"><code>localstorage_clear()</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Clears all <code>localStorage</code> data.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h4>Example in Twig</h4>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">&#123;# Store the user's theme preference client-side #&#125;
&#123;&#123; localstorage_set('theme', 'dark') &#125;&#125;

&#123;# Remove a temporary flag #&#125;
&#123;&#123; localstorage_remove('onboarding_seen') &#125;&#125;</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Security Considerations</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Encryption:</strong> All cookies are encrypted with your <code>APP_KEY</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>HttpOnly:</strong> By default, cookies are not accessible via JavaScript, preventing XSS attacks.</li>
        <li><strong>SameSite:</strong> Defaults to <code>Lax</code>, protecting against CSRF.</li>
        <li><strong>Secure:</strong> By default, cookies are only sent over HTTPS (set <code>secure=false</code> only for local development).</li>
        <li><strong>LocalStorage:</strong> Data is stored in plain text in the browser – never store sensitive information (like passwords or tokens) in <code>localStorage</code>.</li>
    </ul>

    <hr>

    <h2>Testing</h2>
    <p>
        In your PHPUnit tests, you can mock the cookie functions or use the <code>Cookie::get()</code> and <code>Cookie::set()</code> methods as usual. For <code>localStorage</code>, the generated JavaScript is not executed in unit tests, so you may want to test the generation logic separately.
    </p>
{% endblock %}